    <title>McDonald’s busted ice cream machines can now be fixed — legally</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="A photo showing someone holding an ice cream at McDonald’s" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/eiznpGvoFgh5Q3Do_zoeuhiWYk0=/0x108:3401x2375/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73677809/1152831609.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Photo by Gerald Matzka/picture alliance via Getty Images&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="kszvbw"&gt;McDonald’s always-broken ice cream machines might finally get easier to fix. That’s because the &lt;a href="https://public-inspection.federalregister.gov/2024-24563.pdf?utm_campaign=pi+subscription+mailing+list&amp;amp;utm_medium=email&amp;amp;utm_source=federalregister.gov"&gt;US Copyright Office granted&lt;/a&gt; an exemption &lt;a href="https://publicknowledge.org/public-knowledge-ifixit-free-the-mcflurry-win-copyright-office-dmca-exemption-for-ice-cream-machines/"&gt;allowing third parties&lt;/a&gt; to diagnose and repair commercial equipment — including the ones that make your McFlurries.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="LA7BwL"&gt;Now, franchise owners will be able to break through the digital locks that have blocked them from repairing McDonald’s ice cream machines for years. According to the Copyright Office, the exemption will allow people to diagnose, perform maintenance, and repair “retail-level commercial food preparation equipment.” McDonald’s ice cream machines have become so notorious for breaking that someone even &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2020/10/22/21529477/mcdonalds-mcbroken-bot-ice-cream-machines-app-engineering"&gt;created a tool to track broken machines&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="qCRMY6"&gt;The decision is part of the Copyright Office’s final...&lt;/p&gt;
